 <text>
  <front>
   <head>Written at Mr. Pope's House at Twickenham, which he had lent to Mrs. G—lle. In August 1735.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="1" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">GO, Thames, and tell the busy town,</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Not all its wealth or pride</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Cou'd tempt me from the charms that crown</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">That rural flow'ry side:</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="2" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="5" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Thy flow'ry side, where POPE has plac'd</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">The Muses' green retreat,</l>
     <l n="7" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">With ev'ry smile of Nature grac'd,</l>
     <l n="8" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">With ev'ry art compleat.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="3" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="9" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">But now, sweet bard, thy heav'nly song</l>
     <l n="10" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Enchants us here no more;</l>
     <l n="11" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Their darling glory lost too long</l>
     <l n="12" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Thy once lov'd shades deplore.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="4" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="13" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Yet still for beauteous G—lle's sake,</l>
     <l n="14" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">The Muses here remain;</l>
     <l n="15" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">G—lle, whose eyes have power to make</l>
     <l n="16" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">A POPE of ev'ry swain.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
